      body: `German has TWO ways to say 'you' — and using the wrong one is a real social mistake.

SIE (formal, always capitalised)
Use with: strangers, colleagues you don't know well, older people, anyone in a professional setting, shop staff, doctors, professors, anyone who hasn't explicitly invited informality.
Sounds like: 'zee'
Rule of thumb: If you wouldn't immediately be on first-name terms with this person in your home country, use Sie.

DU (informal)
Use with: friends, family, fellow students (especially at university), children, people your own age who've invited it, and in very casual social settings.
Rule of thumb: If in doubt, use Sie. A German will tell you if you can switch: 'Wir können uns duzen' (We can use du with each other).

When someone offers du to you, accept with: 'Ja, gern.' (Yes, gladly.) or 'Danke, ich heiße...' (Thanks, I'm called...).`
