      h: "At the Checkout — An der Kasse",
      body: `Zahlen Sie bar oder mit Karte? — Are you paying cash or by card?
Ich zahle mit Karte. — I'm paying by card.
Ich zahle bar. — I'm paying cash.
Haben Sie Kleingeld? — Do you have change?
Bitte eine Tüte. / Ich brauche eine Tüte. — Please a bag. / I need a bag.
Ich brauche keine Tüte, danke. — I don't need a bag, thank you.
Haben Sie eine Payback-Karte? — Do you have a Payback loyalty card?
Kann ich den Bon haben? — Can I have the receipt?
Das stimmt so. — Keep the change. (literally: that's right as it is)
Ich glaube, das ist falsch. — I think this is wrong.
Entschuldigung, ich habe vergessen... — Excuse me, I forgot...
Kann ich das umtauschen? — Can I exchange this?

CULTURAL NOTES ABOUT GERMAN SUPERMARKETS:
German checkouts are famously fast. Pack immediately — a queue is forming behind you. Consider using a crate/box instead of a bag for speed.
Pfand (deposit): Look for the Pfandautomat (bottle return machine) near the entrance. It's 0.25€ per PET bottle or can.
Most shops are closed Sunday (Sonntagsöffnungsverbot). Plan your shopping accordingly.
Bags cost 0.10-0.30€. Bring your own (Einkaufstasche or Jutebeutel).
Some smaller supermarkets only accept EC-Karte (German bank card), not always credit cards. Always have cash.
Discount stores (Aldi, Lidl): different product placement weekly. Middle aisle = rotating special offers (often good quality).`
